It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations which at one time were beset by an enduring rivalry which spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  The high-water mark of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico and secured for itself Texas and the American Southwest as new territory.  Many other clashes happened between the two nations, finally abating just before the First World War.   The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed on key issues such as religion, culture and tradition and had a major clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
	This is not unlike many other nations who have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor.  Nations which share a border tend to have clashes of interests which lend to the creation of rival positions between the nations.  The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations which share a common border.  David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).  Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States.   
	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

I want to study social work. I want to work with Division of Family and Children Services. I want to help children who are abused or neglected. I also want to support troubled families.

I can give the following values to social work: service, respect, ethics, and help improve relationships. These values are important for me.

I always wanted to help others but did not know what career to follow. In high school and college, I saw people run away from problems or use bad ways to deal with them. This made me study psychology.

After college, I was unsure of my career. One day, I visited a friend. She had a sixteen-year-old boy who was abused by his parents. I went to his parents' house to help. The police asked me to talk to them. They said they could not help the boy. I asked the parents about the situation. They were nervous and blamed the boy. This made me think about social work.

Social justice is also important. Society says individuals are important. But we often copy others. I am unique. I do not want to follow traditions. I protested against social injustice in high school and college. I will continue to do this.

This paper talks about two models for sleep problems, like insomnia. The biological model looks at genes and health problems. The sociocultural model looks at how the environment affects people's sleep based on race, ethnicity, and their income. This review of insomnia uses these models and studies related to them. The research and its findings are then explained and critiqued for their strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep problems can be main sleep problems, sleep problems from other mental problems, or sleep problems from other health issues. Main sleep problems are called Dyssomnias or Parasomnias. Other sleep problems can happen because of medical issues or drug use. Dyssomnias are problems like Primary Insomnia or Primary Hypersomnia. Parasomnias are problems like Nightmare Disorder or Sleepwalking Disorder. This review focuses on insomnia and primary sleep problems in general.

The biological model of sleep problems looks at genes, inherited problems, and how sleep problems affect the body. Neurons in the brain control sleep and wakefulness. A study with mice found that a specific part of these neurons controls sleep. When this part is blocked, sleep problems can happen. This means that people who have this problem may have trouble sleeping naturally. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if someone inherits this problem, they may have trouble sleeping. This can affect their life by making it harder to focus and do daily tasks.

This paper tells about three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it explains what CAPD is. Then, it explains how to diagnose it. Finally, it tells how a teacher in a classroom can help a student with CAPD.

CAPD is when the brain cannot process things that are heard correctly. People with CAPD can hear normally. The brain does not work as it should to separate words or understand what is heard.

The first time CAPD was mentioned was in the 1950s, called "auditory imperception". A research team started testing children with communication problems in 1954. In 1961, Kimura introduced a test to understand the brain's workings. A meeting in 1977 helped with more research.

CAPD can show up in different ways. A person might have trouble hearing sound in space, or have trouble hearing more than one sound at once. They might not understand sound patterns or changes in speech. One sound might block another. They might not understand the sequence of sounds. There is no one test or cause for CAPD. Many tests use questions or stimuli to see how the patient hears.

To diagnose CAPD, a patient needs to be tested by experts like audiologists or speech-language pathologists. They use different ways to test how well the patient hears. There is no cure for CAPD.

Twelfth Night says that using disguise can help with deception. But it can also make it hard to end the deception. People may feel alone. They may have to choose between their own safety or keeping their relationships. In Viola’s case, she needs to pretend to be a man. She does this to protect herself. But it also makes her feel apart from women. Olivia thinks Cesario is her husband. Orsino feels love for Cesario. But these feelings are maybe not real. Shakespeare shows how deception can make people deal with hidden feelings. Viola helps Olivia and Orsino see these feelings. Olivia may love women, not just men. She quickly changes her feelings after seeing Sebastian. So, Twelfth Night shows how disguise can help with hidden feelings, but it also makes people feel alone.

German colonial rule was known for its harsh treatment. Many people talked about it. For example, the German empire killed many Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa. But the German empire was different in different places. German colonies had many kinds of policies and styles of ruling. The schools they built were also different. In German East Africa, the British found many educated Africans when they took over in 1919. In Kamerun and other colonies, people praised German education. But in South West Africa, the mission schools taught most Africans. The government only helped a little. They built schools and helped some missionary schools for Europeans. This had a big effect on South West Africa. Most people there were not educated. Many reasons caused this. This paper talks about these reasons and the settlers' and colonial leaders' views of African people. Many books discuss German colonial education. Most are in German. Some are from before the 20th century. Some later books compare different colonies. One book by Cohen talks about South West Africa and East Africa. It shows why their school systems were different. South West Africa had a warm climate and many white people. East Africa had a large settler population. So, people in South West Africa had a different school system.

Popular music has many types, or genres. It is hard to list all of them because there are so many. Many genres have smaller types, or sub-genres. One of these is Heavy Metal, which is a type of rock music. Heavy Metal has many emotions, mostly dark ones. It is very different from other music.

Heavy Metal started about 40 years ago. It is a movement, not just a genre. A movement is when people keep making new music by changing the old one. It has many dark qualities, and it is often influenced by drugs. This makes the music very different.

Heavy Metal music has many themes from other genres. It started with songs like "Helter Skelter" by the Beatles. "Helter Skelter" was a response to a song by the Rolling Stones. The Beatles wanted to show they could be as heavy as the Stones.

Today, Heavy Metal has many small groups with their own styles. It is hard to say what Heavy Metal is because there are so many types. But it is a movement that keeps changing.

Before the Surrealists painted their dream-like pictures, Henri Rousseau created his own dreams on canvas. "The Dream" from 1910 shows a woman in a dream, but it also shows Rousseau's personal dreams and goals. He wanted recognition, acceptance, and praise from other artists. This was a difficult choice: follow the popular styles or be unique. "The Dream" shows this struggle.

Henri Rousseau was born in Laval, France, on May 21, 1844. His father was a tinsmith. Rousseau had no art training. He worked for the government until he was forty. After his wife and children died, he turned to painting for comfort. Unlike other artists, he painted like a common person.

Rousseau wanted to be accepted by the art world. He started painting late and worked with other known artists. Jan Gordon writes in his book "Modern French Painters" that Matisse and Rousseau were different, even though they were both artists. Matisse was afraid of painting in a simple way, while Rousseau wanted to paint something simple to be accepted.

Many people say that ethics and aesthetics are connected. I think this is true. John Keats says, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Most of what we know comes from education or experience. But we often understand ethics and beauty without learning them. Both ethics and aesthetics are ways to describe, not to give rules. We try to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral. But we can't always explain it. For example, people often say, "There's just something about it" when they talk about their favorite art or literature. I think both art and morals have something special that can't be fully explained. Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." Wittgenstein says, "Ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." This "something" is what makes art and morality powerful. I think ethics and art are connected because we feel them in a special way. This is like how Immanuel Kant talks about the noumenal. Both art and ethics impact us in a way that can't be fully explained. Literature is even more connected to ethics. McKean says, "Literature is important to us because of the values it has."

Germany today is a strong country. It has a unique culture. This culture is found from Munich, near the Alps, to Kiel, by the Baltic Sea. The culture is also felt in Cologne, near the Rhine River. It goes through the center of the country to Dresden, on the Elbe River.

Germany today comes from many places and tribes. Scholars and historians argue about the origins of the name "Germany". Some say it comes from a tribe called Tungrians, who later became known as Germans. They crossed the Rhine and fought against the Gauls. Others say it comes from a spear used in warfare, known as a "ger". Still others say it means "to shout" in the Gaulish language, because the Germans were loud.

Germania is the old name for Germany. The Romans, who lived in Rome, did not want to live in Germania. They sent their soldiers to Germania to fight and trade. The Romans took goods and skills from the Germans. But they mostly lived in their own land.

A Roman historian named Tacitus wrote about the Germans in 98 AD. He said the Germans were not mixed with other races. He also said the weather and land were not good for living.

I looked at the bowl of brown mess in the toilet. My mind was empty. I was not thinking about anything. My eyes saw the mess but my brain did not understand it. I got a book to learn how to draw. It taught me to look at a picture and see it as simple shapes. I tried to use this idea to see the mess. But I was so shocked I could not think. I tried to clean the mess with my hand and the toilet brush. I could not move it. So I used toilet paper to wrap the brush. Then I cleaned the mess with the brush. I was tired and dirty. It was hard work. But I did it.

Teens are dying in car accidents. Many reasons cause this problem. The teen brain is not ready for driving. They are also not experienced. This means more accidents and problems like vehicle rollover, speeding, and driving off the road. Teens also have more accidents when they drive with their friends.

The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found that the more passengers, the more accidents. California and other states try to make teen driving safer by limiting driving hours and forbidding other teens as passengers. But these are only temporary fixes. The main problem is that teens can't handle the risks of driving well.

Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman thinks 18 is too young for a driver's license. He says teens under 19-20 like to take risks. So, it's better to delay driving until this desire goes away. If we keep giving driver's licenses to young teens, more teens will die in car accidents.

By 2010, many more teens will be driving. It's important to protect them. We can do this by making a law. Schools can teach driving, but no one under 18 can drive a car. A provisional license can be given before a full license. But no one under 18 can drive alone. The number of training hours can be based on what most states require.

The idea is not new. We can pass this law to protect teens across the country.

I looked at many old films from the Edison Library. I decided to watch all the trick films from 1895 to 1901. There were fifteen in total. These films use tricks to make illusions. I mainly studied how the trick films are made and how some of the later films are different. Most trick films from that time are made in a small set, with no camera movement. They use long and medium shots, and one shot equals one film. Some films break these rules by using many shots.

Most trick films from that time are made in a small set. The camera does not move. This is like a stage in a theater. Trick films often show actors moving side-to-side. They do not walk towards or away from the camera. For example, in the film "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900), actors move left and right. The camera does not follow them.

The shots in trick films are usually long or medium. Close-up shots are never used. This is like the theater and vaudeville. Actors do not move toward the camera, so close-ups do not happen.

Most trick films have one shot for each idea. This makes trick films short, usually just a minute. They often show tricks, like magic or disappearing acts. But one shot that looks like one idea may actually be many shots joined together to make the illusion.

The film "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895) shows this. At first, it seems like one shot. But looking closely, we see that the "head" shot starts later. So, the whole film is not one shot, but several joined together.

John Taylor from Caroline was a early supporter of the Republican Party. He grew up as a farmer and had a short career in politics. This shaped his strong beliefs in personal freedom and government. He loved farming and believed it was the best way to live. His opinions on government and the Constitution came from his experiences as a farmer.

Taylor thought the United States could create an ideal government because it had no old traditions to follow. He believed in the natural rights of people. These rights are important for everyone and should not be controlled by the government. He thought that in a city, only the strongest and smartest people would become successful. But in a society, everyone must work together.

To make a good society, Taylor said the government must understand the good and evil in people. He believed that the best government protects private property, helps agriculture, and stops capitalism. He thought a good government would work even if the leaders were not good. Self-interest is normal, but it becomes bad if it harms others. A good government is needed to control people's evil side.

Taylor wanted a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He thought the Federal government should have only the powers listed in the Constitution. He knew a big government would be expensive and might be bad. But he also thought a simple interpretation could be dangerous and corrupt. He believed the Declaration of Independence was the true charter of the United States because it more clearly says the country is made of independent states.

In Figure 17, there was a big drop in commuter log submissions in the third month. It was sad, and we don't know why. Winter in New England may have hurt the number of people who commuted by bicycle or foot. December also ends the fall semester. People might not have finished schoolwork and grades yet. The holiday season also brings a month-long break. Classes start again in late January. The low number of submissions in February is harder to explain. Maybe people get excited at first, then lose excitement. We tried the Carpool Challenge Week in March to get more logs. It worked, but we needed to keep the project going. People like driving their cars. To make them try other ways, we gave out gift cards for prizes. We thought bigger prizes might help, like a bicycle or a hybrid car. These prizes didn't change. If we added bigger prizes later, it might have helped. In the end, the prizes seemed good, but bigger prizes might have helped more.

An ETF is like a security that tracks an index, commodity, or group of assets. It offers benefits like an index fund, but it trades like a stock on an exchange. You can sell short, buy on margin, and buy just one share. ETFs have low costs, but you pay a commission for each trade. They offer many choices. For this study, we will look at the ETF IHF and compare it with its top 10 holdings to see if owning one ETF is as good as own 10 stocks and if there's a better way to pick the stocks.

We will only include the top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF's assets. We will calculate how well these stocks represent the ETF and compare their return and beta. The results show that a portfolio of the top 10 stocks could give higher returns and lower beta than the ETF. But we need to check if these results are statistically different.

Edgar Allan Poe wrote a poem, "Dream-Land," which he said was one of his best. In this poem, Poe mentions "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56. This term comes from Virgil, who wrote about an island north of Britain that was the end of the known world. However, Poe might also have gotten this term from German writer Johann Wolfgang von Goethe.

Poe's poem has many similarities with a poem called "The King of Thulé" from Goethe's "Faust." In "The King of Thulé," a king loses his wife and starts drinking heavily. He feels lonely and decides to die. This king's story is like the lonely speaker in "Dream-Land," who is haunted by dead friends and sees a dark, colorless world.

Poe used the term "Thulé" twice in his writings. He used "ultma Thulé" in "The Pit and the Pendulum." He also used "Thulé" at the start and end of "Dream-Land." Both poems can be seen as connected. In "Dream-Land," the speaker says he goes to Thulé and sees a dark, lonely place. This is like the king in "The King of Thulé," who feels alone and wants to die.

Goethe was a famous writer. Poe might have known his work because Poe admired Alfred, Lord Tennyson. Poe said he liked Tennyson's writing. Also, many people copied Goethe's work after his death.

In California, a person who slips and falls in a store might get extra money for pain and suffering. This is called punitive damages. The store manager must have acted with bad intent, like wanting to cause harm or carelessly ignoring possible harm. The judge will not quickly dismiss the claim. The person must show that the manager knew the harm was likely and did not care. In this case, the store manager was told of the spill twice and did nothing for 30 minutes. Before the spill, other people had slipped and fallen. The manager did not act to keep the store safe. The law says the store can be punished if it acts with oppression, fraud, or malice. The judge will consider if the manager's actions were terrible and with a willful disregard for safety. The manager might be sued for these extra damages.

Four years ago, I took a class about Islam at CBC. Many people talked about if Islam is a hostile religion. This question is still important today. After 9/11, I saw the media change from being against Islam to accepting it. In 2001, we could not have had a president like Barack Obama, who has a Muslim family background.
In the Prophet Muhammad's biography, I found something interesting. It says Muhammad was not like he was in history. I thought he forced people to become Muslims. But the biography says he was a martyr. People came to him and saw the truth in his teachings.
The biography also has stories like Jesus's miracles. For example, Muhammad made food for forty people from mutton and milk. This makes Muhammad seem like a humble prophet. But this is like taking credit for Jesus's life.
Many stories in the biography are about people converting to Islam. But the stories come from others who heard from others. This makes the stories seem less true.
What bothers me most is the biography's idea that Muhammad was a godly, humble man. But history says he was not. I believe Muslims today should know the truth about Muhammad's rise to power.

The beliefs Jesus taught and the ideas he held during his lifetime were quickly forgotten when Christianity began to change and grow after his death. The history of Christianity has seen it move away from its original teachings. Today, many people are becoming more aware of this trend. They want to understand what Jesus really taught and not just what others have added over time. This desire will increase in the future. In the end, people will go back to the original ideas of Jesus. This change will happen in the United States and Europe. The church will become strong again, but it will be more like it was in the time of Jesus. People will believe and practice the same way. History shows that this has happened before. For example, the Roman Empire became Christian and our country went from slavery to leadership. In the future, people will read Jesus' words as stories, not just as facts. So, what has changed since Jesus' time? If we look back far enough, we see that Christianity began with Judaism. It had one God, revealed scriptures, and different groups of people.

I think The Jungle shows that people are naturally selfish and only care about themselves. They want to make their own life good, not help others.

The book shows this in several ways. The factory owners and managers only want big factories. They do not care about people or animals hurt by their factories. They do not care about workers.

Upton Sinclair's book says, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair shows that owners do not care about pollution.

Owners and managers also did not care about workers. They did not care about workers' safety or well-being. There were no laws to help workers. Workers lived in terrible conditions. They had no way to leave. Unions did not always help workers. They made money from workers.

The book says workers were like slaves. It says, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many authors use different methods to make readers feel or think certain ways about important topics. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses these methods in his book, The Great Gatsby. He often combines an adjective with a noun that usually do not go together. He also gives meaning to symbols and uses them. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald uses colors like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink to show readers certain feelings.

Fitzgerald makes white/gray mean uniformity. White is nicer and higher class, while gray is older and faded. He shows this in the beginning of the book. Daisy and Jordan are always in white, Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby's party, and Tom wears a white shirt when he meets Myrtle. The only time people are not wearing white is when Nick sees Gatsby's party with bright colors. Fitzgerald also uses white and gray to describe common subjects. For example, Jordan and Daisy had a white girlhood together, and there are gray cars and gray land in the valley of ashes.

After giving white/gray meaning, Fitzgerald uses them to show the unimportance or uniformity of certain things. He first does this with Daisy. After a long time without using these colors, he describes Daisy as dressed in white in a little white roadster. Readers start to see Daisy as less important, just something Gatsby wants. Fitzgerald uses this technique to make Daisy less important, for example, with Daisy's gray fur collar and her white dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County grows many crops because of its warm, sunny weather. Common crops include tomatoes, oranges, lettuce, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. People in the area like organic food. Many local groups sell this food. They have long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Some organic farms give tours and let people hike or watch birds. This helps the landowner get money and teach people about farming. Organic farming has more bugs and weeds than regular farming. It also needs more workers and costs more. However, it helps animals and plants live in the area. The land chosen for this idea is near the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County. It is 160 acres with chaparral, grassland, and oak trees next to the Cleveland National Forest. This area is home to many animals and plants, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the California gnatcatcher. Native Americans lived here for a long time. Then, cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers used the land. The land was a homestead patent and used for grazing and wood. To help the farmer, I looked at government programs and organic farms in the area.

Culture is important in negotiations.
Culture is not simple. It is not the same for all people or places.
It is not correct to say that "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are friendly."
It is better to understand how a culture affects a negotiation.
When meeting a new culture, it is easy to compare it to your own.
To understand a foreign culture, study its history and beliefs.
Do not judge or try to change a culture.
Accept the culture and work within its rules.
Respect traditions and beliefs to move the negotiation forward.
Culture can exist within companies, not just countries.
A company's culture affects its work and people.
Understand the company's values to know what is important.
If a culture values community or saving face, a negotiator will not cause problems for others.
A negotiator from a hard-bargaining culture will not settle quickly.
Learn about the other person to make the negotiation successful.

The quote, "The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God,'" is from Psalm 14 and is at the start of St. Anselm's argument. It is also believed by Thomas Aquinas. They both believe in the God of the Bible. We will compare their arguments.

First, St. Anselm's argument is about finding God within our understanding. He thinks that God's existence is inside our minds. We don't need outside evidence. This is called faith. It is different from Thomas Aquinas's argument.

Thomas Aquinas thinks we can prove God using reason and evidence. He has five logical arguments: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each shows that God's existence is logical. He believes logic can convince people to believe in God without faith.

Long ago, a man named Siddhartha Gautama, who is now called Buddha, was born. He left the world and became enlightened. His teachings started Buddhism. The most common type of Buddhism is Theravada Buddhism, which is over 2,500 years old. Today, it looks different than it did in Buddha's time. For example, in Sri Lanka, monks and people take part in a water-cutting ceremony. This is not something Buddha taught. Many changes happened in Theravada Buddhism over time. This happened because of forces from inside and outside the Buddhist community. These changes can be friendly or harmful.
In this discussion, we will use some special words. "Internal" means something that comes from Buddhists, like monks or laypeople. "External" means something that comes from non-Buddhists. "Hostile" means something that hurts the Buddhist community. "Benign" means something that doesn't want to hurt or help the community. We will use these words often.
First, let's learn about the basics of Buddhism. Buddhists believe in the Triple Gem: Buddha, Dhamma (teachings), and Sangha (community). The Dhamma has three parts: Sutta Pitaka (Buddha's words), Vinaya Pitaka (rules), and Abhidhamma Pitaka (metaphysical ideas). Important ideas include Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (life is suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Learning these helps end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. When people become enlightened, they stop having lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). In the Vinaya Pitaka, there are rules for life. Laypeople follow five precepts (I won't kill, lie, steal, misbehave, or take intoxicants). Monks follow many more rules. The most important idea in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: life is suffering, attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico had a long rivalry from 1836 to 1893. The biggest fight was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848. The United States won and got Texas and the American Southwest. Many other fights happened too, but they stopped before World War I.

This is like many other countries that fight with their neighbors. The United States and Mexico are not alone. They are like Cuba, which also had problems with the United States. Other Latin American countries had good relations with the United States.

Religious issues made the two countries not trust each other. The United States was against Catholicism, which was Mexico's religion. This was like the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 fights between Mexico and the United States. Most fights were about land. Bandits from Mexico attacked towns in the United States. Both countries used military force to stop this.

Schmitt (1974) says the rivalry ended because Mexico became dependent on the United States. The United States stopped trying to take more land and instead helped Mexico with business.

Fifteen years ago, I became suddenly ill. I did not know this illness existed. I was a nurse. I chose this job because I wanted security and safety. I also wanted to help people. Although my dream was to be a scientist or journalist, I chose nursing. Now, I am disabled. I cannot work. I have no money. I live on Social Security Disability. I need help from my family and friends. I am not strong when disaster happens. I agree that we should not depend on big government. But we should trust each other and help each other. In the past, people helped each other in hard times. My point is that we should be prepared for emergencies, but we should also trust each other. I have a disaster kit. I have first aid supplies and canned goods. I am ready for emergencies. But I also get to know my neighbors.

Why do living things change over time? Are there rules or limits that guide these changes? In 1917, D’Arcy Thompson said, “Even now, zoologists have not begun to express basic organic shapes in mathematical terms.” Today, mathematical modeling is used to study the growth of shells, like those in the Prunum group. Our study combines these models with experiments to understand how Prunum shells change. We use X-ray images and a program called CerioShell to create models of shell shapes. These models help us see how shells can change. We also study real shells and experimental results to better understand big changes in this group over time.

A shell is like a tube that grows and changes over time. It turns around in a spiral shape, called a whorl. The central column of the shell is called the columella. The speed of the whorls can change, and a line separates each whorl, called a suture. The largest whorl is called the body whorl, and the end with the opening is called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed from different angles. The usual view is looking at the aperture, with the apex pointing up. To count the whorls, start by looking at the shell from the top. Find the first suture and draw a line. Count the whorls from this line, rounding to a quarter whorl.

A shell can also be seen as a series of openings that change over time. The path of these openings can be drawn and calculated. Once this is done, we can change some things to see how the shell grows differently.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia did not change much in the last ten years. Indonesia is close to meeting some Millennium Development Goals, like water and sanitation targets. However, the improvements in child and maternal health are not enough to reach the goals by 2015. We will discuss the reasons for this and how to improve the health system. Indonesia made good progress in the number of births with skilled health workers, but traditional workers like midwives cannot provide medical help if the pregnancy is complicated. This means the number of maternal deaths is still high. There is also a decrease in the number of children under five treated for diarrhea by a health professional. Postnatal care is incomplete, and rates are low across the country. Cesarian-section rates are low, with 4% overall, 7% in urban areas, and 2% in rural areas. This shows that healthcare services are focused in urban areas. There is also a big gap in service use between the poorest and richest people. Now, we need to decide how to improve neonatal and maternal care. Should we focus on program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system? Program-specific approaches can be effective and manageable. However, they can also mean less funding for other areas and human resources going to the area with more resources. Running many programs for one area can lead to duplication and uncoordinated services.

Victorian novels are usually about details and the rich. Two novels, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They use mystery and strange things. This makes the characters more interesting. They show why characters act and feel.

“And now, many confusing ideas come to Oliver's mind. He seems still talking to Sikes and Crackit, who argue. He hears their words. Suddenly, he jumps back. He sees lights and noise. He feels pain and fear. An unseen hand takes him away. All this happens in his mind.”

In Oliver Twist, this happens through dreams. These dreams show what Oliver feels and thinks. When he remembers the shooting, he feels it again. He feels no control over his life. He is in danger, but he cannot stop it. His friend Fagin might have made him like this. In the end, Oliver cannot save himself.

Two years ago, I worked in an after school program. I helped children with their studies. I was good at English and reading. One child, Adrian, had trouble reading. He spoke perfect English, but he had strange problems with letters. Some he knew and others he did not. His mother only spoke Spanish. With my bad Spanish, we communicated. Then it became clear: Adrian read well, but he did not know the English alphabet. This helped him, but I don't know if it helped much. I tell this story to show the language barrier problem in schools, especially in California. Even if a child speaks perfect English, reading can be hard. The solution is not simple. It needs many things: dual language system, mainstream immersion, tutors, ESL classes. Each child is different. The key is to use all of these together.

From the time we are children, most of us hear about something bigger than we are. Some go to church, temple, or search inside themselves for answers. Some accept the religion passed down by their parents. Others strongly reject it. Whatever path we choose, we try to find part of ourselves through our own beliefs. We search for a light in the dark to guide us out of the shadows.

My father loved cardinals. One day, we sat on our porch, listening to the rain. He looked out, half remembering, half searching. He had lost weight and his hair was thin. He avoided eye contact, and I felt alone and afraid. I hugged him, sat close, and watched the rain like him.

My father died in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. Chemo and radiation did not help. I did not want to watch him die. I remembered how he lived, not how he died. I stayed in my bed for three days, waiting for news. No one called me.

The Gothic Novel is an "old-new" idea, as Ian Watt describes it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. People have liked and disliked the Gothic mode. Some think it has no real depth, while others say it is 'terrible sublime'. The Gothic Novel started with The Castle of Otranto by Horace Walpole. He used old and new ideas to create this genre. He used old theatrical elements and new mimicry of nature in modern novels. Walpole called it "A Gothic Story". The Gothic mode uses many old traditions from medieval times. Even then, the word "gothic" meant many things, like styles, people, and periods. It was seen as old or unsophisticated. The mix of old and new in Gothic lets it last for a long time. Gothic becomes new to readers far from the original writing.

One main idea in Gothic novels is chivalry. The Gothic Novel used the idea of chivalry, the training of knights, from medieval times. Chivalry was important to Gothic writers because it showed the perfect knight. They saw a lack of this ideal in society. Through chivalry, Gothic writers made the past seem ideal and romantic. This showed the future of Gothic and Romantic. Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto during a troubled time. He was worried about the future. He thought the good in people from the Gothic era had been lost. In his story, Frederic is a perfect example. He is a prince, has suffered, and is supposed to be dead. He has many chivalric traits. His story uses the Gothic idea of excess.

Supply chain management is the way goods move from the customer order through the raw materials stage, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. The term "supply chain management" was invented in 1982 by Keith Oliver. He described how to plan, do, and control the whole process to satisfy customers quickly and well. There are six important parts of a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these parts to give the best service to customers.

Production is the first step. It is the start of the whole process. Managers must know what customers want. They look at the market to decide what customers need. Once they understand, they decide what products to make and how many. They also choose where to make the products and which plant is best for volume and quality. Then, they schedule work and maintain equipment. Production is very important. If details are not planned well, it can cause problems later.

The second important part is supply. Supply is about making strategic decisions to decide a facility's core abilities and which outsourcing partners to use. A company may have different divisions for one product. Each division has different equipment and workers. Managers must decide which one is best for each production process. They may also choose to outsource to other companies to find fast, good, and flexible ways to reduce costs.

Hitler is alive in Burma. Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street. Her sign says this. Burma is an Asian country. It is ruled by a bad group. They took power in 1962. They stopped people from protesting in 2007. Many people, especially monks, protested peacefully. The government did not like this. They used force. Many people died. A journalist was killed. Official numbers are low, but a soldier said many more died. This is not new. Many governments have done this. Early Roman and Japanese leaders thought they were gods. Our current president talks to a leader of a funny group. Examples of bad things these groups have done are Tiananmen Square, Rwanda, and Hitler's Third Reich.

Duke Ellington's success in jazz comes from his long career and his ability to lead his orchestra. His piano playing is often not the main focus, but he was a great composer. He created complex pieces that showed the talents of each band member. Ellington made sure each player could improvise. He also wrote pieces that showed the sound of the whole orchestra. This helped him create some of the best pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary says Ellington's sound and creativity are shown in his early piece, "Creole Love Call." Here, he used the voice like a musical instrument. This piece has six parts. In the first part, the voice and reeds play together. The voice starts smooth and then becomes rough. In the second part, a muted trumpet plays the main melody. The third part has a high clarinet solo with a piano background. The fourth part is like the first one but with brass and reeds. The fifth part is the most exciting, with reeds playing the main melody and brass and rhythm sections playing syncopated stops. The sixth part is like the first one but the voice sounds like a growl. The ending is a vocal run and a trombone's dissonant sound.

In "Hot and Bothered," Ellington combines his ability to write tight music with his sense of tone color. A call and response between Bubber Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing uses both the vocal parts of Miley's playing and the instrumental parts of Cox's voice to make a rich sound. The piece "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's muted trombone to create a great melody.

Ellington's use of voice to add tone color is a style that is seen in many of his pieces.

She always felt like something was missing. This desire was still there when she was 14 and 17. She wanted a boy, but none interested her. She did not know why. She had theories, but no answers. She lived her life with questions.

A calm day at home was peaceful. Her parents were good and calm. They rarely argued, even with her. She was independent and full of energy, so they argued about her freedom. Today was not calm. She heard a short scream in the kitchen. Her mother was on the ground in pain. She ran to help. Her mother told her to take her to the hospital. She carried her mother to the car and drove.

At the hospital, she saw doctors. They took her mother to be looked at. She sat and waited, worried.

Her mother fell off a stool trying to reach a vase on high shelf.

This study looked at a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) to see if it can lower the risk of heart disease and stroke. The Med diet has more fruits, vegetables, and fish, and less meat and fat. It also lets some alcohol. Past studies showed that this diet can help with weight loss and cholesterol levels, but not much about stroke.

This study watched 74,886 women for 20 years. They filled out food questionnaires six times. Most of the women kept doing it. They reported heart disease and stroke. Deaths were checked in records. The study also looked at things that might make the results wrong, like age, smoking, and exercise.

The study found that the Med diet can lower heart disease and stroke risk. Women who followed the diet the most had less risk of these problems. This was true for women who had heart attacks and strokes. They had 71% less risk than those who did not follow the diet well.

In 2007, the United States had a big problem. Many people lost their jobs, and many important companies went into trouble. This is called a recession. We need to know how this happened and how to stop it. The financial crisis started because politicians made bad decisions. They asked banks to give loans to people who could not repay them. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac also helped these bad loans by selling them to others. When those people did not pay back, the banks had no money and did not know what to do. This made the whole economy bad.

In 1999, during the Clinton era, the president wanted to be popular. He relaxed rules about who could get loans. This made it easier for people to get loans they could not pay back. This was a bad decision, and it helped cause the financial crisis later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times wrote about this in 1999. He said that Fannie Mae, a big company that helps with loans, was under pressure from the government and its stockholders. Holmes said that if the economy got bad, the government might have to save Fannie Mae, like it did with savings and loan companies in the 1980s. This is what happened.

Many things made the economy get bad, like new kinds of loans. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were used a lot. These made people and businesses get money they could not pay back. This made the economy very weak. When the housing market crashed, many banks lost a lot of money. Bear Stearns, Merrill Lynch, and Lehman Brothers were in big trouble. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac also had a lot of bad loans. They were put under government control in 2008.

Exposition is important part of the story. It tells the reader what happens before the action starts. But too much exposition makes the story boring. Dr. Merlin hates long passages of text that do not show the story.

The first rule is "Show, don't tell." This means to use action and dialogue to tell the story, not just tell the reader what happens. For example, instead of telling the reader that the heroine loves her husband, show her actions and words that prove it.

Another problem is telling too much too fast. The reader does not want to read a long list of the character's hobbies and past. Instead, give the reader clues about the character through their actions and words in the story. Then, the reader will understand the character's past and future better.

Exposition should be like a puzzle. The reader should figure out what happened by finding clues in the story. This makes the story more interesting and engaging.

Remember, exposition is not something to get out of the way quickly. It is a part of the story that should make the reader want to know more. So, be careful with exposition. Make it interesting and engaging, and your readers will be glad you did.

I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first was from NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who stabbed his wife. They did not say her name, but his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot. He looked very bad. They talked about this story for about two minutes.

The second story was about a boy named Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area. He was very hurt and there were no arrests yet. The SWAT team was investigating. This story was short. I think this was because it happened in a black neighborhood. I have noticed that minorities are not often told about in the news when they are victims of crime. If a white child or adult is missing or hurt, the media goes crazy. But if someone is black, sometimes it is not even mentioned.

Another story was about a hole in a helicopter. The helicopter is called Med-Flight. They found the hole in it. They said the hole was made by a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. They also said that Crime-Stoppers are giving a five-thousand dollar reward for information leading to an arrest.

The next story was about rain and thunderstorms for Saturday. They said the weekend would be warm, in the mid-eighties. The news about the weather was short, but they wanted people to stay tuned.

They also told about a robbery at a store on Clime Road in Columbus. A dark-skinned black man robbed the store. He was about six feet tall and weighed about 150 pounds. They talked a lot about him being black and how dark he was. I thought this was strange.

Another story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug kingpin in Texas. He was sentenced to 25 years in prison for selling drugs. They said he was Hispanic, but I don't think that was important to the story.

Brothers have a strong bond. It cannot be broken. This bond includes many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other. They see themselves when they look at their brother. The bond is clear when a situation is hard. These feelings have a cost. Understanding these feelings is important. When a brother looks at another brother, he sees his own reflection. He sees himself as he truly is. The theme of this bond is shown in "The Scarlet Ibis". Two brothers go on a journey. Their feelings are shown through their actions and the narrator's words. The main character, Doodle, feels pride. He wants his brother to be like him. He wishes his brother could do things like hold his breath, run, jump, or climb. But his brother is weak. He cannot do these things. The main character is upset. He wants to harm his brother. But he loves his brother too. He melts when his brother smiles at him. The bond is shown through their actions and feelings.

The human brain is a complex system for processing information. As technology advanced, so did the ways people describe it. First, it was compared to a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and now, a computer. Remember, these metaphors have limits and can lead to mistakes.
Information starts with the senses. They turn things like touch, heat, sounds, and light into electrical signals. The brain changes these signals over and over again, both from the bottom up and from the top down. For example, when you see a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing helps you see it as a box. Top-down processing helps you recognize it as a black box.
After processing, an attention filter decides if the signal is important. For example, you can hear your name in a noisy room, but not every blade of grass when looking at your shoes. There are many steps in processing, and attention changes the results many times.
For the brain to process information, it must store it. There are different types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Information is first encoded in a certain way. Verbal input can be like the word's look (structural), sound (phonemic), or meaning (semantic). Once stored, information must be kept. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for 20 seconds, is kept by looping electrical signals. Long-term memory is kept in the structure of certain proteins.
There are many models of how knowledge is organized in the brain. One model is the semantic network. It says there are nodes for concepts, and they are linked by how related they are. For example, "chair" is linked to "table," which is linked to "wooden."

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of technology and capitalism in Brave New World. People value community over the individual and are made happy from birth. The World Controller controls everything. Huxley uses Marxist ideas to show problems with these systems. He says capitalism makes people think they are good when they are not. People do not know the truth about their place in society. They only care about money and happiness. Classes are controlled. They do not know they are being controlled. They do not care about each other. They only think about sex and money. Brave New World shows how technology and capitalism make people lose their free will and feelings. People do not know how to love or have deep feelings. They only think about their bodies and what they can get. They do not care about each other or their place in society.

I live at University Park for two and a half years. Many students, like me, find it hard to get around campus. My freshman year, I lived in East Halls, far from the center. Walking to Willard Building took up to 25 minutes, especially in bad weather. Now, that empty space is filled with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As our campus grows, getting around becomes harder. The best solution is the bicycle. However, students must use it, and the campus must be built for cyclists.

My friend who rode a bike a few years ago said, “Biking is the only way to get around.” It is good for your body and efficient. A bowl of oatmeal and some exercise can take you 30 miles. Like many students, I live off campus. I bought a bike this year to cut my commute to Thomas Building. Walking to Thomas takes 25 minutes. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes. Though Pollock Road is the best route, it is not always easy to ride on. Walking is an option, but I am too busy. If I didn’t have a bike, walking would be my only choice. Walking to Thomas would take an extra 30-40 minutes each day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Adding time for other classes and appointments, I can’t spare that much time.
