This is like many other countries that fight with their neighbors. The United States and Mexico are not alone. They are like Cuba, which also had problems with the United States. Other Latin American countries had good relations with the United States.

Religious issues made the two countries not trust each other. The United States was against Catholicism, which was Mexico's religion. This was like the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 fights between Mexico and the United States. Most fights were about land. Bandits from Mexico attacked towns in the United States. Both countries used military force to stop this.

Schmitt (1974) says the rivalry ended because Mexico became dependent on the United States. The United States stopped trying to take more land and instead helped Mexico with business.

Fifteen years ago, I became suddenly ill. I did not know this illness existed. I was a nurse. I chose this job because I wanted security and safety. I also wanted to help people. Although my dream was to be a scientist or journalist, I chose nursing. Now, I am disabled. I cannot work. I have no money. I live on Social Security Disability. I need help from my family and friends. I am not strong when disaster happens. I agree that we should not depend on big government. But we should trust each other and help each other. In the past, people helped each other in hard times. My point is that we should be prepared for emergencies, but we should also trust each other. I have a disaster kit. I have first aid supplies and canned goods. I am ready for emergencies. But I also get to know my neighbors.

Why do living things change over time? Are there rules or limits that guide these changes? In 1917, D’Arcy Thompson said, “Even now, zoologists have not begun to express basic organic shapes in mathematical terms.” Today, mathematical modeling is used to study the growth of shells, like those in the Prunum group. Our study combines these models with experiments to understand how Prunum shells change. We use X-ray images and a program called CerioShell to create models of shell shapes. These models help us see how shells can change. We also study real shells and experimental results to better understand big changes in this group over time.

A shell is like a tube that grows and changes over time. It turns around in a spiral shape, called a whorl. The central column of the shell is called the columella. The speed of the whorls can change, and a line separates each whorl, called a suture. The largest whorl is called the body whorl, and the end with the opening is called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed from different angles. The usual view is looking at the aperture, with the apex pointing up. To count the whorls, start by looking at the shell from the top. Find the first suture and draw a line. Count the whorls from this line, rounding to a quarter whorl.

A shell can also be seen as a series of openings that change over time. The path of these openings can be drawn and calculated. Once this is done, we can change some things to see how the shell grows differently.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia did not change much in the last ten years. Indonesia is close to meeting some Millennium Development Goals, like water and sanitation targets. However, the improvements in child and maternal health are not enough to reach the goals by 2015. We will discuss the reasons for this and how to improve the health system. Indonesia made good progress in the number of births with skilled health workers, but traditional workers like midwives cannot provide medical help if the pregnancy is complicated. This means the number of maternal deaths is still high. There is also a decrease in the number of children under five treated for diarrhea by a health professional. Postnatal care is incomplete, and rates are low across the country. Cesarian-section rates are low, with 4% overall, 7% in urban areas, and 2% in rural areas. This shows that healthcare services are focused in urban areas. There is also a big gap in service use between the poorest and richest people. Now, we need to decide how to improve neonatal and maternal care. Should we focus on program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system? Program-specific approaches can be effective and manageable. However, they can also mean less funding for other areas and human resources going to the area with more resources. Running many programs for one area can lead to duplication and uncoordinated services.

Victorian novels are usually about details and the rich. Two novels, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They use mystery and strange things. This makes the characters more interesting. They show why characters act and feel.

“And now, many confusing ideas come to Oliver's mind. He seems still talking to Sikes and Crackit, who argue. He hears their words. Suddenly, he jumps back. He sees lights and noise. He feels pain and fear. An unseen hand takes him away. All this happens in his mind.”

In Oliver Twist, this happens through dreams. These dreams show what Oliver feels and thinks. When he remembers the shooting, he feels it again. He feels no control over his life. He is in danger, but he cannot stop it. His friend Fagin might have made him like this. In the end, Oliver cannot save himself.

Two years ago, I worked in an after school program. I helped children with their studies. I was good at English and reading. One child, Adrian, had trouble reading. He spoke perfect English, but he had strange problems with letters. Some he knew and others he did not. His mother only spoke Spanish. With my bad Spanish, we communicated. Then it became clear: Adrian read well, but he did not know the English alphabet. This helped him, but I don't know if it helped much. I tell this story to show the language barrier problem in schools, especially in California. Even if a child speaks perfect English, reading can be hard. The solution is not simple. It needs many things: dual language system, mainstream immersion, tutors, ESL classes. Each child is different. The key is to use all of these together.

From the time we are children, most of us hear about something bigger than we are. Some go to church, temple, or search inside themselves for answers. Some accept the religion passed down by their parents. Others strongly reject it. Whatever path we choose, we try to find part of ourselves through our own beliefs. We search for a light in the dark to guide us out of the shadows.

My father loved cardinals. One day, we sat on our porch, listening to the rain. He looked out, half remembering, half searching. He had lost weight and his hair was thin. He avoided eye contact, and I felt alone and afraid. I hugged him, sat close, and watched the rain like him.

My father died in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. Chemo and radiation did not help. I did not want to watch him die. I remembered how he lived, not how he died. I stayed in my bed for three days, waiting for news. No one called me.

The Gothic Novel is an "old-new" idea, as Ian Watt describes it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. People have liked and disliked the Gothic mode. Some think it has no real depth, while others say it is 'terrible sublime'. The Gothic Novel started with The Castle of Otranto by Horace Walpole. He used old and new ideas to create this genre. He used old theatrical elements and new mimicry of nature in modern novels. Walpole called it "A Gothic Story". The Gothic mode uses many old traditions from medieval times. Even then, the word "gothic" meant many things, like styles, people, and periods. It was seen as old or unsophisticated. The mix of old and new in Gothic lets it last for a long time. Gothic becomes new to readers far from the original writing.

One main idea in Gothic novels is chivalry. The Gothic Novel used the idea of chivalry, the training of knights, from medieval times. Chivalry was important to Gothic writers because it showed the perfect knight. They saw a lack of this ideal in society. Through chivalry, Gothic writers made the past seem ideal and romantic. This showed the future of Gothic and Romantic. Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto during a troubled time. He was worried about the future. He thought the good in people from the Gothic era had been lost. In his story, Frederic is a perfect example. He is a prince, has suffered, and is supposed to be dead. He has many chivalric traits. His story uses the Gothic idea of excess.

Supply chain management is the way goods move from the customer order through the raw materials stage, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. The term "supply chain management" was invented in 1982 by Keith Oliver. He described how to plan, do, and control the whole process to satisfy customers quickly and well. There are six important parts of a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these parts to give the best service to customers.

Production is the first step. It is the start of the whole process. Managers must know what customers want. They look at the market to decide what customers need. Once they understand, they decide what products to make and how many. They also choose where to make the products and which plant is best for volume and quality. Then, they schedule work and maintain equipment. Production is very important. If details are not planned well, it can cause problems later.

The second important part is supply. Supply is about making strategic decisions to decide a facility's core abilities and which outsourcing partners to use. A company may have different divisions for one product. Each division has different equipment and workers. Managers must decide which one is best for each production process. They may also choose to outsource to other companies to find fast, good, and flexible ways to reduce costs.

Hitler is alive in Burma. Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street. Her sign says this. Burma is an Asian country. It is ruled by a bad group. They took power in 1962. They stopped people from protesting in 2007. Many people, especially monks, protested peacefully. The government did not like this. They used force. Many people died. A journalist was killed. Official numbers are low, but a soldier said many more died. This is not new. Many governments have done this. Early Roman and Japanese leaders thought they were gods. Our current president talks to a leader of a funny group. Examples of bad things these groups have done are Tiananmen Square, Rwanda, and Hitler's Third Reich.

Duke Ellington's success in jazz comes from his long career and his ability to lead his orchestra. His piano playing is often not the main focus, but he was a great composer. He created complex pieces that showed the talents of each band member. Ellington made sure each player could improvise. He also wrote pieces that showed the sound of the whole orchestra. This helped him create some of the best pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary says Ellington's sound and creativity are shown in his early piece, "Creole Love Call." Here, he used the voice like a musical instrument. This piece has six parts. In the first part, the voice and reeds play together. The voice starts smooth and then becomes rough. In the second part, a muted trumpet plays the main melody. The third part has a high clarinet solo with a piano background. The fourth part is like the first one but with brass and reeds. The fifth part is the most exciting, with reeds playing the main melody and brass and rhythm sections playing syncopated stops. The sixth part is like the first one but the voice sounds like a growl. The ending is a vocal run and a trombone's dissonant sound.

In "Hot and Bothered," Ellington combines his ability to write tight music with his sense of tone color. A call and response between Bubber Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing uses both the vocal parts of Miley's playing and the instrumental parts of Cox's voice to make a rich sound. The piece "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's muted trombone to create a great melody.

Ellington's use of voice to add tone color is a style that is seen in many of his pieces.

She always felt like something was missing. This desire was still there when she was 14 and 17. She wanted a boy, but none interested her. She did not know why. She had theories, but no answers. She lived her life with questions.

A calm day at home was peaceful. Her parents were good and calm. They rarely argued, even with her. She was independent and full of energy, so they argued about her freedom. Today was not calm. She heard a short scream in the kitchen. Her mother was on the ground in pain. She ran to help. Her mother told her to take her to the hospital. She carried her mother to the car and drove.

At the hospital, she saw doctors. They took her mother to be looked at. She sat and waited, worried.

Her mother fell off a stool trying to reach a vase on high shelf.

This study looked at a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) to see if it can lower the risk of heart disease and stroke. The Med diet has more fruits, vegetables, and fish, and less meat and fat. It also lets some alcohol. Past studies showed that this diet can help with weight loss and cholesterol levels, but not much about stroke.

This study watched 74,886 women for 20 years. They filled out food questionnaires six times. Most of the women kept doing it. They reported heart disease and stroke. Deaths were checked in records. The study also looked at things that might make the results wrong, like age, smoking, and exercise.

The study found that the Med diet can lower heart disease and stroke risk. Women who followed the diet the most had less risk of these problems. This was true for women who had heart attacks and strokes. They had 71% less risk than those who did not follow the diet well.

In 2007, the United States had a big problem. Many people lost their jobs, and many important companies went into trouble. This is called a recession. We need to know how this happened and how to stop it. The financial crisis started because politicians made bad decisions. They asked banks to give loans to people who could not repay them. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac also helped these bad loans by selling them to others. When those people did not pay back, the banks had no money and did not know what to do. This made the whole economy bad.

In 1999, during the Clinton era, the president wanted to be popular. He relaxed rules about who could get loans. This made it easier for people to get loans they could not pay back. This was a bad decision, and it helped cause the financial crisis later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times wrote about this in 1999. He said that Fannie Mae, a big company that helps with loans, was under pressure from the government and its stockholders. Holmes said that if the economy got bad, the government might have to save Fannie Mae, like it did with savings and loan companies in the 1980s. This is what happened.

Many things made the economy get bad, like new kinds of loans. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were used a lot. These made people and businesses get money they could not pay back. This made the economy very weak. When the housing market crashed, many banks lost a lot of money. Bear Stearns, Merrill Lynch, and Lehman Brothers were in big trouble. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac also had a lot of bad loans. They were put under government control in 2008.

Exposition is important part of the story. It tells the reader what happens before the action starts. But too much exposition makes the story boring. Dr. Merlin hates long passages of text that do not show the story.

The first rule is "Show, don't tell." This means to use action and dialogue to tell the story, not just tell the reader what happens. For example, instead of telling the reader that the heroine loves her husband, show her actions and words that prove it.

Another problem is telling too much too fast. The reader does not want to read a long list of the character's hobbies and past. Instead, give the reader clues about the character through their actions and words in the story. Then, the reader will understand the character's past and future better.

Exposition should be like a puzzle. The reader should figure out what happened by finding clues in the story. This makes the story more interesting and engaging.

Remember, exposition is not something to get out of the way quickly. It is a part of the story that should make the reader want to know more. So, be careful with exposition. Make it interesting and engaging, and your readers will be glad you did.

I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first was from NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who stabbed his wife. They did not say her name, but his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot. He looked very bad. They talked about this story for about two minutes.

The second story was about a boy named Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area. He was very hurt and there were no arrests yet. The SWAT team was investigating. This story was short. I think this was because it happened in a black neighborhood. I have noticed that minorities are not often told about in the news when they are victims of crime. If a white child or adult is missing or hurt, the media goes crazy. But if someone is black, sometimes it is not even mentioned.

Another story was about a hole in a helicopter. The helicopter is called Med-Flight. They found the hole in it. They said the hole was made by a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. They also said that Crime-Stoppers are giving a five-thousand dollar reward for information leading to an arrest.

The next story was about rain and thunderstorms for Saturday. They said the weekend would be warm, in the mid-eighties. The news about the weather was short, but they wanted people to stay tuned.

They also told about a robbery at a store on Clime Road in Columbus. A dark-skinned black man robbed the store. He was about six feet tall and weighed about 150 pounds. They talked a lot about him being black and how dark he was. I thought this was strange.

Another story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug kingpin in Texas. He was sentenced to 25 years in prison for selling drugs. They said he was Hispanic, but I don't think that was important to the story.

Brothers have a strong bond. It cannot be broken. This bond includes many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other. They see themselves when they look at their brother. The bond is clear when a situation is hard. These feelings have a cost. Understanding these feelings is important. When a brother looks at another brother, he sees his own reflection. He sees himself as he truly is. The theme of this bond is shown in "The Scarlet Ibis". Two brothers go on a journey. Their feelings are shown through their actions and the narrator's words. The main character, Doodle, feels pride. He wants his brother to be like him. He wishes his brother could do things like hold his breath, run, jump, or climb. But his brother is weak. He cannot do these things. The main character is upset. He wants to harm his brother. But he loves his brother too. He melts when his brother smiles at him. The bond is shown through their actions and feelings.

The human brain is a complex system for processing information. As technology advanced, so did the ways people describe it. First, it was compared to a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and now, a computer. Remember, these metaphors have limits and can lead to mistakes.
Information starts with the senses. They turn things like touch, heat, sounds, and light into electrical signals. The brain changes these signals over and over again, both from the bottom up and from the top down. For example, when you see a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing helps you see it as a box. Top-down processing helps you recognize it as a black box.
After processing, an attention filter decides if the signal is important. For example, you can hear your name in a noisy room, but not every blade of grass when looking at your shoes. There are many steps in processing, and attention changes the results many times.
For the brain to process information, it must store it. There are different types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Information is first encoded in a certain way. Verbal input can be like the word's look (structural), sound (phonemic), or meaning (semantic). Once stored, information must be kept. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for 20 seconds, is kept by looping electrical signals. Long-term memory is kept in the structure of certain proteins.
There are many models of how knowledge is organized in the brain. One model is the semantic network. It says there are nodes for concepts, and they are linked by how related they are. For example, "chair" is linked to "table," which is linked to "wooden."

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of technology and capitalism in Brave New World. People value community over the individual and are made happy from birth. The World Controller controls everything. Huxley uses Marxist ideas to show problems with these systems. He says capitalism makes people think they are good when they are not. People do not know the truth about their place in society. They only care about money and happiness. Classes are controlled. They do not know they are being controlled. They do not care about each other. They only think about sex and money. Brave New World shows how technology and capitalism make people lose their free will and feelings. People do not know how to love or have deep feelings. They only think about their bodies and what they can get. They do not care about each other or their place in society.

I live at University Park for two and a half years. Many students, like me, find it hard to get around campus. My freshman year, I lived in East Halls, far from the center. Walking to Willard Building took up to 25 minutes, especially in bad weather. Now, that empty space is filled with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As our campus grows, getting around becomes harder. The best solution is the bicycle. However, students must use it, and the campus must be built for cyclists.

My friend who rode a bike a few years ago said, “Biking is the only way to get around.” It is good for your body and efficient. A bowl of oatmeal and some exercise can take you 30 miles. Like many students, I live off campus. I bought a bike this year to cut my commute to Thomas Building. Walking to Thomas takes 25 minutes. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes. Though Pollock Road is the best route, it is not always easy to ride on. Walking is an option, but I am too busy. If I didn’t have a bike, walking would be my only choice. Walking to Thomas would take an extra 30-40 minutes each day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Adding time for other classes and appointments, I can’t spare that much time.
